<TEXT>
a prominent candidate seeking reelection to 
japans parliament was attacked and injured near the capital on 
tuesday evening by an assailant wielding a steel rod 
koichi hamada 61 of the governing liberal democratic party 
was struck repeatedly on the head with a 16inch rod as he left a 
hall after a campaign rally in kimitsu a police official said 
wednesday 
a suspect 27yearold minoru uzawa was arrested at the scene 
in chiba prefecture 20 miles east of tokyo 
it was the third attack directed at a japanese politician in a 
month and the second on a conservative candidate in three days 
after the attack hamada was taken to a nearby hospital for 
treatment of head injuries which were described as requiring 10 
days to heal said the police official who declined to be named 
uzawa is a member the inagawakai one of the nations largest 
criminal syndicates the official said police booked him on 
charges of inflicting bodily injury 
uzawa was quoted by police as saying he had attacked hamada 
because he disliked him investigators were looking into his 
motives the official said 
hamada who is seeking to be returned to the house of 
representatives for a seventh time has held such posts as 
directorgeneral of the defense agency and chairman of the partys 
public relations committee a 1980 gambling scandal led hamada to 
resign from parliament for one term but he was reelected to his 
seat in 1983 
tuesdays attack followed an apparently unrelated shooting 
incident at the campaign office of former prime minister yasuhiro 
nakasone in takasaki 60 miles northwest of tokyo on sunday a 
23yearold member of a rightist group was arrested on the spot no 
injuries were reported 
in another attack mayor hitoshi motoshima of nagasaki was shot 
in the back jan 18 as he left city hall a member of a rightist 
group has been charged with attempted murder in the case 
rightist groups which often include gang members have been 
criticizing nakasone and other governing party leaders for their 
alleged involvement in the massive bribery and influencepeddling 
scandal known as the recruit affair motoshima has been the target 
of rightwing death threats for remarks he made about the late 
emperor hirohitos war role 
</TEXT>
