<TEXT>
the associated press has announced plans for 
testmarketing an audiotex service that will allow ap member 
newspapers to provide readers with voice information services 
without any capital costs 
the test of the new nationwide 900number service was announced 
tuesday at the talking newspapers audiotex conference 
the ap will set up a centralized computer operation that will 
allow member newspapers to make stock quotes and business headlines 
available to their readers over a nationwide paypercall network 
newspapers will not have to buy a computer or acquire phone lines 
for the system 
the service will be testmarketed with a limited number of 
newspapers during the spring and if successful will be offered 
to all ap members 
for the past five years ap has been providing audiotex services 
to members who operate standalone audiotex systems these services 
include stock quotes sports scores weather and audio briefs 
covering general business sports and agricultural news from ap 
those services will still be available to members of the news 
cooperative 
with audiotex newspapers can broaden their coverage in their 
local communities said chris pederson aps sales manager for 
information services in essence newspapers become a 24hour 
sevendayaweek information source only a phone call away from 
their readers 
in the new service newspapers will pay an initial setup fee 
and agree to promote the service through house ads in their 
publication newspapers will receive a royalty check monthly for 
calls made to the service by their readers each service will be 
customized to carry the name of the participating newspaper 
</TEXT>
