<TEXT>
un food relief operations in northern ethiopia 
have been suspended due to the fighting between eritrean rebels and 
government forces around the strategic port of massawa an official 
said 
rebels of the eritrean peoples liberation front last week 
claimed to have captured control of massawa the larger of two 
ports on ethiopias red sea coast 
relief organizations ship most of their food aid to massawa for 
eventual distribution by land to northern ethiopia where an 
estimated 4 million people are afflicted by drought mostly in the 
warravaged provinces of eritrea and tigre 
we dont know what will happen in the long term said paul 
mitchell of the romebased world food program that would only be 
speculation 
he said wfp headquarters has been unable to make contact with 
its 200 staff members in eritrea in the past few days 
he said about 50000 tons of food is currently stored in massawa 
awaiting distribution about 20000 tons came from the world food 
program and the rest from various donors and government 
organizations 
getting food supplies to drought victims was a problem even 
before the new round of fighting began in massawa mitchell said 
it wasnt possible to reach all the people affected but we 
did reach some he said but now this situation has caused for 
the moment even a suspension of that 
fessahazion petros representative of the eritrean rebels in 
rome said the group had attacked the port because ethiopia uses it 
to ship arms to government troops in the area 
he said the rebels who have been fighting for independence for 
their former italian colony since 1962 could distribute the relief 
supplies themselves 
if the food aid has not been destroyed in the fighting i 
think our combatants can distribute it to the population petros 
said 
