was a real need for the changes because most of labels were really 
bad ms lubinsky said there had been some really creative 
efforts to make the labels as illegible as possible 
obviously our industry will comply with it said james 
sanders president of the beer institute although it will 
require changing hundreds of labels on various containers 
labels on many cans and bottles already comply with the new 
more restrictive requirements sanders said 
one change ms koester said is a requirement that the words 
government warning be printed using both capital letters and 
bold type 
other changes involve larger type on larger containers and a 
limit on the number of characters per inch 
the warning reads 
government warning 1 according to the surgeon general 
women should not drink alcoholic beverages during pregnancy because 
of the risk of birth defects 2 consumption of alcoholic 
beverages impairs your ability to drive a car to operate machinery 
and may cause health problems 
type sizes for one and twoliter containers remain the same 
one millimeter for capital letters on the former and two 
millimeters about the size of newsprint on the latter 
the atf increased the size of the type on threeliter containers 
to 3 millimeters or about oneeighth inch 
ms lubinsky said the atf rejected two other proposed changes 
that would require the labels to be placed in a box on the front of 
the containers the regulations permit the warning to be placed 
virtually anywhere on a bottle or can 
sens strom thurmond rsc and albert gore dtenn were 
