<TEXT>
the worlds two nuclear superpowers should 
move to prevent the accidental or unauthorized launch of nuclear 
weapons by placing sensors in each others missile fields and 
destruct systems on strategic missiles a ussoviet foundation 
says 
the proposal tuesday by the moscowbased international 
foundation for the survival and development of humanity founded 
by the late soviet physicist and political activist andrei sakharov 
was made as an alternative to the strategic defense initiative 
under research by the united states 
the foundations report has been submitted to rep les aspin 
dwis chairman of the house armed services committee together 
with the proposal that its recommendations be debated jointly by 
the house panel and the supreme soviets defense committee 
former president reagan billed star wars as sdi is informally 
called as a continentspanning protective umbrella to foil a 
soviet missile attack but the bush administration endorses a more 
modest research concept 
although tensions between washington and moscow are being 
sharply reduced some administration officials maintain a missile 
defense system could fend off a missile launched by accident or 
fired by terrorists or a hostile third world nation 
andrei kokoshkin deputy director of the soviet institute of usa 
and canadian studies said at a news conference tuesday that the 
report is aimed at countering this argument for star wars 
at the pentagon an official who commented on condition he not 
be identified said some of the reports recommendations could be 
discussed at arms control negotiations 
but he said the united states already has in place a range of 
effective measures designed to prevent accidental or unauthorized 
launches of nuclear weapons 
and he said there are legitimate concerns a radical third world 
nation could develop or obtain nuclear weapons and launchers 
existing technology probably could fashion a defense against a 
nuclear attack on the united states by such a state even though 
the means are not in hand to counter a fullscale soviet missile 
attack 
the report says installing sensors on the missile silos and 
launchers of each side would eliminate the danger that a missile 
strike could be launched because of a false alarm 
the sensor systems would continually transmit preprogrammed 
continually changing coded signals via relay sensors as long as no 
missiles were launched and the sensors were not tampered with it 
said 
it said if an earlywarning satellite or radar indicated an 
enemy missile was launched the absence of a corresponding 
indication from the sensors would be evidence that the warning was 
a false alarm 
the report also called for greater central controls over nuclear 
weapons including installation of socalled permissive action 
links on nuclear weapons to prevent their use without secret 
authorization codes 
the pentagon official said most new us nuclear weapons have 
such devices 
the authors of the report called on both the united states and 
the soviet union to begin urgent studies by all the nuclear powers 
on the possibility of placing destruct devices on ballistic 
missiles to destroy or disarm them before they hit their targets 
this would enable the destruction of a missile launched by 
mistake or without proper authority 
the pentagon official said the united states did not put 
destruct devices on ballistic missiles because their reliability 
was uncertain 
i think it is easier to prevent something from being launched 
than to destroy it after it is already gone he said 
</TEXT>
