<TEXT>
us and soviet trade negotiators working 
under orders to wipe away nearly a halfcentury of trade friction 
between the two superpowers say they are on schedule to get the 
job done by june 
both sides expressed satisfaction with the progress made after 
an initial two days of talks aimed at drawing up a treaty to 
normalize trade between the two nations 
president bush and soviet president mikhail s gorbachev would 
like to sign such an agreement at their next summit meeting in 
june the bush administration believes freer trade between the two 
nations would provide an important economic boost to the political 
reforms gorbachev is making 
deputy us trade representative julius katz the top us 
negotiator in the talks said the next meeting has been tentatively 
scheduled for later this month in europe with a third bargaining 
session to be held in midmarch in vienna 
i dont have any doubt that we can get the job done he told 
reporters after the talks ended tuesday there was nothing that 
came up that presents an insuperable obstacle 
chief soviet negotiator yuriy chumakov saying that the opening 
discussions had gone fairly well indicated that one key 
sticking point could be the terms under which the treaty might be 
suspended 
the us side is insisting that language be included giving the 
united states the right to suspend the treaty if the soviets are 
found after an annual presidential review to be violating 
requirements for open emigration policies 
the soviets want to negotiate a threeyear trade treaty without 
the threat of suspension arguing that the assurance of trade 
stability is needed to attract us business investment 
would you invest 1 billion if you knew the agreement was 
valid for only one year chumakov asked reporters 
annual review of soviet emigration policies is required by the 
jacksonvanik amendment which congress passed in 1974 in 
retaliation for the soviet governments refusal at that time to 
allow free emigration for soviet jews and other dissidents 
katz said the us negotiating position on this matter cannot 
change unless congress changes the law something not likely to 
occur in the immediate future 
negotiation of a wideranging trade agreement was a primary goal 
established during the bushgorbachev summit last december in 
malta american officials predict that twoway trade between the 
two countries could double or even triple over the next three years 
once the high tariffs imposed by jacksonvanik are lowered 
in the first 11 months of 1989 us exports to the soviet 
union primarily grain shipments totaled 382 billion while 
soviet sales in the united states primarily of petroleum and 
consumer items such as vodka and furs totaled 658 million 
the trade treaty would be used to grant the soviet union most 
favored nation status qualifying it for the lowest tariffs 
available to any other country soviet exports into the united 
states currently bear duties as much as 10 times higher than 
imports from other nations 
by one estimate the price of soviet vodka could drop by 125 
per bottle with the lower tariffs 
american farmers also are watching the trade talks with keen 
interest because the soviets have said they will not sign a new 
grain pact until agreement is reached on a wideranging trade 
treaty 
the current negotiations likely will serve as a prototype for 
similar agreements to lower tariffs for other east european 
nations poland and hungary already have received most favored 
nation status and the united states is considering granting 
similar low tariffs for czechoslovakia romania bulgaria and east 
germany 
katz said the pace of negotiations with other nations would 
depend on when free elections are held with czechoslovakia a 
good bet to be next in line to receive the lower tariffs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

