two men were acquitted on charges of 
illegally exporting to japan logs cut from federal land in what was 
believed to be the first time anyone had been tried for violating 
the law 
a federal court jury tuesday acquitted log dealer john j 
tortorelli of bellevue wash and parttime dealer winston bentley 
of spokane wash of all charges 
tortorelli and bentley were accused of having the logs federal 
markings sawed off because they knew they were for export 
federal law prohibits the export of raw logs cut from national 
forests the logs must be processed in us mills where prices are 
much less than foreign mills 
jack davis a us forest service investigator said he was 
surprised that the men were acquitted but said the fact the jury 
chose to believe the defendants is indicative of the complexity 
of investigations of that type 
preparation of the case took two years he said 
tortorelli was accused of buying truckloads of logs cut on 
forest service land in western montana northern idaho and eastern 
washington in 1987 and 1988 and then selling them to japanese 
exporting companies on the west coast 
bentley a church janitor helped inspect and handle some of the 
timber at a processing center in mead wash prosecutors said 
prosecutors believed the case was the first time anyone was 
prosecuted for violating the export ban 
the defense argued that any export of the logs handled by 
tortorelli and bentley was accidental and that the men should not 
be punished for any unintentional violations of federal law 
the government gave immunity to truck drivers duane farmer and 
roger britz of emunclaw wash in exchange for testimony that was 
expected to substantiate the charges however their testimony 
largely supported the defenses version of events 
