one of the two remaining allmale eating 
clubs at princeton university has voted to admit women but two 
more rounds of voting must be conducted next year before female 
students can join 
the ivy club formed in 1879 voted 5123 tuesday to allow 
women said robert garrett the clubs undergraduate president 
club policy states that two consecutive votes must be held to 
alter rules garrett said the second vote will be next year 
followed by a vote by the graduate board made up of princeton 
alumni 
the ivy club and the tiger inn are the only two of the schools 
13 private eating establishments that do not admit women most 
juniors and seniors take their meals at the clubs which are housed 
in private homes near the campus 
their exclusion of women was challenged in state supreme court 
last week by princeton graduate sally frank now a faculty member 
at new york law school 
ms frank backed by the state attorney generals office and 
princeton university argued that the clubs have a symbiotic 
relationship with the university that removes them from 
protection under the laws governing private organizations she said 
they are subject to the states antidiscrimination laws 
attorneys for the two clubs argued that they are similar to 
fraternities and sororities and have the right to choose their own 
members 
ms frank said her case and recent picketing by students and 
faculty put pressure on the ivy club 
garrett said members voted as they did for different reasons 
and that the club as a whole believes strongly it has a 
constitutionally protected right of association that lets it 
determine its own membership 
