<DOCNO> AP900214-0098 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two star wars satellites 
rocketed into space wednesday to test a plan to destroy enemy 
missiles by bouncing deadly laser beams off orbiting mirrors 
a mirror on one of the satellites was designed to reflect lasers 
fired from a mountaintop in hawaii back to a ground target to 
assess the accuracy of a system for intercepting ballistic missiles 
sensors on the second payload were to measure laser strikes in a 
test aimed at correcting laser distortions caused by dust moisture 
and gases as the beam shoots through the atmosphere 
these are key technologies for developing a groundbased laser 
system if we get rid of the distortion in the atmosphere and get 
good accuracy with the laser coming off a mirror it is a major 
step in our program to develop directedenergy weapons said air 
force col william browning one of the project managers 
the satellites were carried aloft by a 12story delta rocket 
that roared off its launch pad right on time at 1115 am 
the tracking chart shows the vehicle right down the middle of 
the track its right on target launch commentator ray adams 
reported minutes after liftoff 
success of the mission could help preserve much of the 45 
billion that president bush has requested for research in budget 
year 1991 for the program formally known as the strategic defense 
initiative some members of congress want to cut deeply into that 
amount 
the beambouncing satellite called relay mirror experiment 
carried a 24inch diameter mirror designed to point a laser beam 
with an error of less than 57 millionths of a degree 
the experiment will use two ground stations on maui hawaii one 
is at the air force maui optical station located on the summit of 
mount haleakala the second is about 12 miles away at the base of 
the mountain 
both ground stations will aim lowpowered laser beams 
simultaneously at the 2300pound satellite orbiting 270 miles up 
rme will use those two beams as signals to orient its mirror when 
the mountaintop station aims another beam at the satellite the 
beam should reflect off the mirror and strike a sensor target at 
the second station 
the tests scheduled to start in about two weeks were scheduled 
to last about eight months with rme passing within range of the 
hawaii stations at least once a day 
the companion satellite is a 3175pound payload called lace 
for lowpower atmospheric compensation experiment its principal 
instrument is a package of 210 lasersensitive sensors packed into 
a square measuring 13 feet on each side 
the mount haleakala laser to be used on lace is equipped with a 
special flexible mirror designed to predistort the laser beam on 
earth in such a way that the expected atmospheric disturbances will 
erase the distortion the result should be a sharp and powerful 
beam by the time it reaches lace orbiting 340 miles high 
previous laser tests using targets on satellites and on space 
shuttles have established a pattern for the type of distortion the 
atmosphere causes 
lace also carries an experiment to acquire and track the exhaust 
plumes of rockets in a test to determine which wavelengths are most 
useful in detecting these plumes another experiment will measure 
neutron levels in space in a test designed to help develop a means 
of distinquishing between enemy warheads and decoys 
the lace experiments are expected to start in about 60 days and 
continue for 30 months 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

