<TEXT>
east germanys heavily industrialized 
economy was long touted as one of the strongest in the east bloc 
but an exodus of workers devastated productivity and has hastened 
moves toward unification with west germany 
when east german leaders opened the countrys borders nov 9 
they were hoping to stop the flight by convincing citizens that 
serious reforms were under way 
but the exodus spiraled bringing the economy closer to 
collapse more than 85000 east germans have come west this year 
joining 340000 who arrived last year 
peter pietsch an economist for the west german bank 
commerzbank said the effect on east germany has been devastating 
in many offices every fourth of fifth employee is missing 
pietsch told the associated press the country could face a 
collapse if this outflow continues 
statistics released tuesday in east germany show how bad the 
situation is industrial production fell 56 percent in january 
1990 compared to the previous year mostly because of the exodus 
the government said the lost productivity has led to a severe drop 
in exports it said 
serious worker shortages have been reported across east germany 
mail is no longer delivered in some areas because theres no one to 
deliver it soldiers are being used to operate trolleys 
strikes and slowdowns by workers who fear they could lose their 
jobs as east germany undergoes democratic change are another factor 
east germanys economy always lagged behind that of western 
industrialized nations but for years it was considered the 
strongest in the soviet bloc churning out industrial goods 
chemicals and other products for itself and other east bloc 
countries 
its average per capita income last year was the highest in the 
east bloc 
but a growing number of east germans are attracted to wealthy 
west germany because of the prospects of living the kinds of lives 
they were denied under 40 years of rigid communist rule 
west germanys own social services in addition to its job and 
housing markets are seriously burdened by the newcomers and the 
dire situation has led to a number of moves toward unification 
in ottawa canada on tuesday it was announced the two german 
states and the four world war ii victors the united states 
britain france and the soviet union would soon begin talks on 
german unification 
on wednesday the west german cabinet approved a supplementary 
1990 budget that provides 345 billion in funding for immediate 
measures to help east germany 
the two german states at west germanys initiation are also 
about to undertake talks on establishing a common currency with 
west germanys powerful deutsch mark the currency for both 
countries 
this would be a giant leap toward unification 
when the idea first arose there was considerable opposition 
from west german financial experts who feared it could result in 
higher taxes and drag down the value of the deutsch mark 
economists are still advising that such a step be taken 
cautiously but support for the idea has grown with acknowledgment 
of east germanys desperate condition 
economists say it will take huge amounts of money to rebuild 
east germanys economy but they believe it can be done in 10 years 
pietsch said west germanys construction industry especially 
sees good possibilities for investment in east germany once 
freemarket economic conditions are established there his 
commerzbank plans to open branch offices in east germany at some 
point 
the machinery and equipment is generally better in east 
germany than in other east bloc countries he said the 
prerequisites are there for a strong economic upswing once 
investments from the west get going he said 
