<DOCNO> AP900214-0114 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the relatively high rate of tuberculosis among 
blacks long blamed on poverty appears to result in part from a 
genetic susceptibility to the disease a study concludes 
the study found that in nursing homes and prisons where the 
races have identical living conditions blacks are twice as likely 
as whites to become infected with tb bacteria 
researchers said they were surprised by their discovery which 
suggests that while crowded housing and other social conditions 
play important roles in spreading the disease genetic factors also 
appear to influence peoples ability to resist tb 
we found that there is a systemic difference between whites 
and blacks said dr william w stead whites seem to be more 
able to fend off the organism without its ever being able to 
establish an infection 
stead happened upon the apparent difference while analyzing 
nursing home and prison statistics at the arkansas department of 
health he reported his findings in thursdays new england journal 
of medicine 
another soontobe published study reports the discovery of a 
racial difference in the way blood cells respond to the tb 
bacteria which could help explain why blacks seem more prone to 
getting tuberculosis 
the arkansas study was based largely on a review of 25398 
elderly people who were free of tb infection when they were 
admitted to nursing homes in the state when they were retested at 
least two months later 14 percent of the blacks and 7 percent of 
the whites showed evidence of tb infections 
prison data from arkansas and minnesota also found that black 
inmates were twice as likely as white prisoners to catch the 
bacteria while incarcerated 
its a very intriguing finding said dr george comstock of 
johns hopkins university i never quite believe anything until 
somebody replicates it but i dont know of any real holes in this 
one 
about 22000 cases of tuberculosis are reported annually in the 
united states resulting in 1700 deaths in the population at 
large tuberculosis is about six times as common among blacks as 
whites 
the disease which attacks the lungs has long been associated 
with poor crowded living conditions an estimated 10 million 
americans are believed to be infected with the bacteria but not 
sick 
dr george curlin of the national institute of allergy and 
infectious diseases called the new findings plausible and 
provocative 
im scared to death that people are going to say this explains 
it all and forget everything else he said of the total six 
times difference what proportion is attributable to biology and 
what to social factors i would say that biology is relatively 
minor 
in his study stead speculated that whites have evolved better 
defenses against tb because the bacteria has long been common in 
europe and parts of africa north of the sahara but is traditionally 
rare in subsaharan africa 
in contrast blacks are genetically more resistant than whites 
to malaria which is common in africa 
in the other study dr alfred crowle of webbwaring lung 
institute at the university of colorado found differences in the 
resistance of germeating blood cells called macrophages in 
blacks these cells are more likely to harbor tb infections 
this helps explain why black people are more susceptible to 
tuberculosis than are white people said crowle 
at the turn of the century tb was the leading cause of death in 
the united states the number of cases fell steadily until 1984 
experts believe the decline has leveled off in part because of 
the emergence of the aids virus which weakens the bodys 
resistance to infections others possible factors include 
homelessness and immigration of people from areas where the disease 
is still common 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

