<TEXT>
business inventories fell in december for the 
first time in more than a year while sales remained unchanged the 
government said wednesday 
its a reflection that the economy has slowed down said 
thomas runiewicz an economist with the wefa group in bala cynwyd 
pa it slowed during the fourth quarter and we expect it to 
remain slow until the summer 
the commerce department said inventories were down 02 percent 
to a seasonally adjusted 7952 billion after rising 05 percent in 
november and 03 percent in october 
it was the first decline since a 01 percent drop in october 
1988 and the largest since inventories slipped 06 percent in 
december 1986 
at the same time sales were flat at a seasonally adjusted 
5225 billion november sales were revised downward from a 07 
percent to a 04 percent gain sales fell 05 percent in october 
runiewicz said the fact that inventories fell at the same time 
sales were flat means businesses were cutting back on production 
but he and other analysts agreed that while the economy is weak it 
is not nearing a recession 
it would take a significant decline in sales to tip the 
balance of economic activity in a negative direction said 
richard w rahn chief economist for the us chamber of commerce 
but government reports on retail sales yesterday already suggest 
that such a decline is not in the cards 
the commerce department reported tuesday that retail sales 
which represent a third of the nations economic activity jumped 
16 percent in january 
the december business activity produced a slight decline to 
152 in the ratio of inventories to sales that means it would 
take 152 months to exhaust inventories at the december pace the 
ratio was 153 in both october and november 
on the whole inventories are in pretty good shape said 
evelina tainer an economist with the first national bank of 
chicago it suggests that even though the economy is sluggish 
we shouldnt need much of a correction in the near term 
if inventories were to pile up excessively it could mean severe 
cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs a situation already 
found in the automobile industry 
chrysler corp ford motor co and general motors corp all 
experienced temporary layoffs in january to reduce the number of 
vehicles on backlots 
retail backlogs dropped 01 percent in december but sales fell 
further down 02 percent 
both inventories and sales at the manufacturing level which 
represent about 45 percent of the total slid 04 percent 
wholesalers inventories were down 02 percent while their 
sales rose 11 percent 
