numbers add up to 101 percent because the percentages were rounded 
off officials said 
however 76 percent of those polled said they thought there was 
something they personally could do to help protect the environment 
such as not littering reducing their use of environmentally 
harmful products and taking part in environmental organizations 
we are tremendously encouraged by these results said jay b 
hair president of the national wildlife federation 
college students are expressing a deep concern for the 
environment and the overwhelming majority are clearly willing to 
do something about it 
ninetyfour percent of those surveyed said they would be willing 
to pay more for products and packaging that are safe for the 
environment and threequarters said recycling of newspapers glass 
and cans should be required by law in all communities 
asked whether people should be willing to sacrifice 
environmental quality for economic growth 42 percent said they 
disagreed strongly another 28 percent disagreed somewhat 8 
percent agreed strongly 18 percent agreed somewhat and 4 percent 
had no opinion 
the survey was conducted in november by hughes research corp of 
rockville md the students between the ages of 17 and 24 were 
enrolled in fouryear colleges or universities about half were men 
and half women 
the federation said that based on the sample size the survey 
results could be considered accurate to within 5 percentage points 
