<TEXT>
proposed stiffer fines and penalties for 
corporate wrongdoers were attacked as too tough wednesday by 
businesses but were endorsed by academics and public interest 
representatives who said the sanctions may not go far enough 
the proposed guidelines are extremely harsh punitive 
unwarranted and will place many businesses on the threshold of 
insolvency earlyn church a director of the national association 
of manufacturers told the us sentencing commission 
she said the commission should delay any recommendations for 
about five years because the panels proposals are based on 
inadequate research 
that prompted an angry rebuke from george e mackinnon a 
federal judge and a member of the commission 
mackinnon noting he had 60 years of experience as a lawyer and 
a judge said im not legislating in the dark we know all about 
corporate crime we might even know more than the national 
association of manufacturers 
amitai etzioni a professor at george washington university 
testified that the commission and congress should ignore the 
selfserving cries of outrage by business interests to deter a 
corporation fines should be set at a level which could not simply 
be absorbed as part of the cost of doing business 
let us not make this a valentines day for those corporations 
with blinders to all but their bottom line he said 
hofstra university law professor carl mayer representing ralph 
naders public citizen lobbying organization said the sentencing 
commissions proposed fines would help deter and punish corporate 
crime 
but he urged the commission to go further and give federal 
judges power to suspend or revoke the right of companies convicted 
of crimes to do business with the government he also said judges 
should have power to publicize convictions of corporations to alert 
shareholders workers and consumers 
joseph digenova a former us attorney here who now represents 
a group of defense lawyers said the sentencing commission is 
moving too rapidly 
new laws give prosecutors and judges adequate tools for 
appropriate sentences and restitution he said he said the 
commission should wait at least two years before adopting 
guidelines and in the interim should recommend a range of sentences 
for judges to follow 
the commission last november unveiled tentative guidelines for 
increased penalties for corporations one proposal calls for fines 
of up to 374 million for the worst offenders 
the panel said then that stiffer sentences will provide a 
strong incentive for owners and managers of organizations to 
strengthen internal mechanisms for preventing officers and 
employees from committing crimes and for detecting and punishing 
such crimes that are committed 
the commission created by congress in 1987 called for public 
comment on its proposals before a final report is submitted to 
lawmakers may 1 the guidelines would become law unless congress 
enacts legislation altering or overturning them 
the proposals would require judges to follow certain 
instructions in determining the size of fines and restitution for 
example penalties would be bigger when top executives aid or 
condone crimes or if the officials tried to block a government 
investigation 
fines would be lower if highlevel executives had reason not to 
be aware of the criminal conduct 
fines for companies formed to engage in criminal activity would 
be large enough to put them out of business 
the guidelines are aimed at punishing businesses and forcing 
them to make restitution but are not directed at punishing 
individual corporate officials 
the commission established sentencing guidelines for individual 
defendants two years ago and their constitutionality has been 
upheld by the supreme court 
