screwworm larvae were discovered in the wound 
of a us soldier injured in panama prompting warnings that the 
pest could infect animals in texas 
screwworms are the larvae or maggots of a blowfly that feed on 
the flesh of warmblooded animals they can kill livestock if the 
animals go untreated 
a 30year program had eradicated the screwworm first in the 
united states and later in mexico 
the soldier was among the first to arrive in san antonio on dec 
20 for treatment at brooke army medical center hospital spokesman 
ray dery said tuesday 
theres just a remote possibility that anything escaped from 
the hospital said paul jensen assistant area veterinarian with 
the us department of agriculture the weather was in our 
favor 
a hard freeze that hit san antonio in late december probably 
killed the larvae which thrive in warm climates officials said 
some of the larvae from the soldiers wound were saved for 
analysis and the rest were disposed of in medical trash and ended 
up at a local landfill dery said 
weeks later entomologists with the national museum of natural 
history in washington identified the samples that were saved as 
screwworm 
were asking any local veterinarian within a 20mile radius if 
they find any larvae infestation in any animal wound to send it to 
our identification lab in mission jensen said 
