najib offered the guerrillas a sixmonth ceasefire and said his 
troops would stop firing longrange scud missiles if the guerrillas 
stopped firing rockets at kabul and other cities 
so far the guerrillas have rejected all truces offered by kabul 
and have refused all negotiations with najib and his peoples 
democratic party of afghanistan 
there was little in najibs invitation that seemed likely to 
entice them to give up their nearly 12yearold attempt to oust the 
ruling party which took power by coup in 1978 
the guerrillas whose headquarters are across the borders in 
pakistan and iran call themselves mujahedeen or islamic holy 
warriors 
najib took office in 1986 he is one of four successive 
sovietbacked leaders to run afghanistan through a series of 
internal party coups and power struggles 
soviet troops entered afghanistan in december 1979 to prop up 
its faltering protege party and started withdrawing in may 1988 
under a unsponsored accord the last red army combat troops 
crossed the border back to the soviet union on feb 15 1989 
the aghan president former head of the dreaded khad secret 
police again proposed creating a national council that would form 
a broadbased coalition government he called for new parliamentary 
elections they would be held without resort to force for 
influencing them and the results would be respected by the kabul 
government he said 
najib also said his government places enormous value to the 
role of the united nations and is ready for cooperation with 
whatever outline the un may table 
he did not address the question of whether he himself would step 
aside during any peace talks but about four hours before his 
speech was broadcast by staterun television najmuddin kawyani a 
member of his partys powerful politburo dismissed this idea 
kawyani told foreign reporters there could be no preconditions 
to any talks 
news reports before and after us secretary of state james 
baker iiis visit to moscow last week said the americans would drop 
their demand that najib resign before any peace negotiations began 
provided he was gone before the talks ended 
during the talks the results of the talks should be clear 
kawyani said it should be decided who should go if the 
americans determine the results before the talks that najib 
should go then the talks will be for what 
najib proposed sending a kabul delegation to talk to mujahedeen 
leaders in peshawar and quetta in pakistan he said the delegation 
should also visit tehran iran where a second mujahedeen alliance 
is based and to europe where afghan exiles opposed to both the 
najib government and the mujahedeen live 
he said if the opposition refused to accept representatives of 
his government or party the delegation could consist of clergymen 
scholars and intellectuals with no affiliations 
the mujahedeen rejected similar offers in the past considering 
any delegates who might be sent from kabul as nothing more than 
najibs henchmen 
he also invited the guerrillas to come to kabul and said they 
are not required at the first stage to meet state and party 
authorities in afghanistan 
he offered restructuring of the economy with a movement away 
from state control of investment and enterprise 
najib said the united states pakistan and saudi arabia 
continued to arm the mujahedeen and denounced them for it 
an english translation of najibs spech delivered in kabuls 
persian dari language was provided by the foreign ministrys press 
center 
kabul complained wednesday in a letter to the un security 
council that pakistan and the united states were intensifying 
aggression against afghanistan in violation of accords aimed at 
ending the war 
it said pakistan was helping in the shipment of military 
supplies and training for the rebels and that the united states 
was delivering advanced weapons 
a spokesman at the pakistan un mission denied the allegations 
and called them part of a propaganda campaign to divert attention 
from kabuls problems a state department official said afghanistan 
has made similar statements in the past and that washington saw no 
merit in the allegations 
</TEXT>
