michigans senate on wednesday overwhelmingly passed a bill 
requiring minors to get permission from a parent or judge before 
having an abortion and south carolina senators unanimously 
approved similar legislation with a twist 
under south carolinas bill parents who deny a daughters 
request for an abortion would have to share legal and financial 
responsibility for her child until the young mother turns 18 
the michigan legislation adopted 298 now goes to the house 
which is expected to pass the restriction 
however democratic gov james blanchard is expected to veto the 
bill setting up an override battle or an attempt by antiabortion 
forces to enact such a law through a petition drive 
the measure adopted wednesday would allow a girl under 18 to 
seek a probate court order allowing an abortion if she couldnt get 
the permission of a parent or adult guardian 
it is the first antiabortion legislation to advance in michigan 
since the us supreme court in july gave states more power to 
restrict abortions pennsylvania last fall adopted the nations 
toughest abortion law but many of its provisions have been put on 
hold because of a challenge from abortionrights groups 
im very positive the house will accept what weve done 
said republican sen fred dillingham manager of the bill in the 
senate 
michigan wants and needs protection for parents and for minors 
with problem pregnancies barbara listing president of right to 
life of michigan said in a statement 
the senate rejected amendments offered by minority democrats who 
called the bill too harsh the most substantive would permit 
consent by another family member and require counseling another 
would allow an abortion in cases of rape or incest 
the bill generated some heated debate although the outcome was 
assured 
today will be a day of infamy for this body said sen john 
kelly a democrat were going to have to live with the despair 
the suicides the backalley abortions these young people have 
committed no crime 
south carolinas bill passed unanimously on a voice vote is 
also the first since the us supreme courts decision 
the state already has a law requiring girls under 16 to obtain a 
parents consent for an abortion but similar laws without a 
judicial consent option have been declared unconstitutional in 
other states and south carolinas ordinance has not been enforced 
under the bill passed wednesday girls under the age of 17 could 
obtain permission for an abortion from a grandparent or guardian in 
addition to a parent or judge 
its not everything that we wanted but its much of what we 
wanted said sen david thomas a democrat and an abortion 
opponent this is the best i could have hoped for 
