<TEXT>
television for years the mythic battleground 
for cops and robbers is becoming as much a part of law enforcement 
equipment as handcuffs and badges 
officers can now learn more about everything from making traffic 
stops to subduing unruly suspects by tuning in to the law 
enforcement television network 
the network went on line full time in july 1989 and since then 
has acquired about 1200 law enforcement agency subscribers 
throughout the continental united states ranging from small 
departments to the fbi said network president billy prince 
the comments were getting back say its the best thing since 
the twoway radio weve been hearing stories of officers staying 
after a shift to watch it prince said 
letns satellite programming available to subscribers 24 hours 
a day monday through friday runs the spectrum from the latest law 
enforcement techniques to police news the network showcased its 
programming last month at the american society of law enforcement 
trainers conference in san diego 
each of the five regular training segments is designed with a 
level of law enforcement in mind from street beat geared 
toward the officer on the beat to command update which 
provides training for supervisors and administrators 
the programs are supplemented by roll call a quarterhour 
of police news and training segments 
our purpose is to train existing officers in the uptodate 
things going on in their profession prince said in a telephone 
interview from his dallas office we let them know whats going 
on and let them know what works and what doesnt work so they dont 
wind up reinventing the wheel 
the network took its cue from a similar project begun in 1986 to 
train auto mechanics and car salesmen prince said in mid1988 
wescott communications began funding what would eventually become 
letn 
the service was initially limited to one day a week now it 
operates on a 10 million annual budget said prince a former 
dallas police chief 
letns staff is mostly exlaw enforcement professionals 
including three former police chiefs technical adviser missy 
olinn who is licensed to practice law in ohio and has a 
background in unarmed selfdefense instruction reviews all 
programs and scripts for content including faithfulness to police 
procedure 
because adults learn from what they see and hear its 
important that all of the details are right olinn said 
thats important we dont want to endanger an officer because of 
the program 
although the network employs no fulltime instructors trainers 
are chosen from among the best in the nation olinn said 
dale stockton training and personnel manager for police in 
carlsbad a coastal town north of san diego said the department 
has been pleased with letn since it became a subscriber in october 
my recommendation would be to continue it stockton said 
it costs this department 488 per month i ask myself for 488 
what else can i do that would effectively deliver such 
comprehensive training as this so far i havent found anything 
one of the networks most notable subscribers the fbi has been 
with letn since its inception although spokesman mike kortan said 
the bureaus public affairs office in washington dc does not 
employ letn for actual training 
i would not characterize them as a training vehicle for the 
fbi for us its sort of a news outlet for the fbi kortan said 
their format allows for a little more indepth stories which is 
a break from the usual short soundbites that were used to 
</TEXT>
