<TEXT>
savers and investors watched with remarkable 
calm this week as a pillar of the financial scene for the past 
decade wall streets drexel burnham lambert inc collapsed 
some specialists in matters of personal finance said the steady 
behavior of the stock and bond markets proided impressive evidence 
of longterm confidence in the economic and investment outlook 
others suggested that decisionmarkers in individual households 
and offices of professional moneymanagement firms alike had 
simply been numbed by a long succession of crises and did not know 
what to do next 
in many ways drexel personified the golden era on wall street 
with its daring and innovation bringing what once was considered 
highrisk debt into the mainstream of the investment world so the 
instant message of its demise seemed to be the 80s are over 
but if a turning point has been reached how should anyone with 
money to manage respond 
is it time to cash in the mutual fund investments abandon plans 
to buy a house and run for the hills or will patience and 
confidence be rewarded for those who sit tight and ride out the 
storm 
few of the experts profess to have any pat allpurpose answers 
to those questions 
but there is ample evidence they say that individual investors 
began months or even years ago to protect themselves from jolts 
like the recent slide in the junkbond market or the 1987 crash in 
stock prices 
last year for instance assets of moneymarket mutual funds 
surged by nearly 100 billion to record highs 
in the nearly two decades since they first appeared money funds 
have become a popular choice for investors seeking to minimize 
their risks in uncertain times 
financial adviser william e donoghue attributes the resurgence 
of money funds now to such factors as excessive real estate loan 
losses and writeoffs of bad loans in general 
as many investors in stock mutual funds know the stock market 
has also been showing the effects of debt worries for some time 
although the dow jones industrial average posted record highs 
last october and in early january most of the market has been in a 
deteriorating phase since last august observes the merrill lynch 
market letter in its current issue 
in the wake of the debt boom furthermore a new financial job 
description is already in vogue on wall street the workout 
specialist looking to find bargains and salvage whatever assets 
remain in the wreckage of deals gone bad 
for the speculatively inclined the supply of bankruptcy bonds 
has increased sharply in recent years said george putnam iii 
editor of the bostonbased turnaround letter 
in 1989 putnam calculates 37 companies with 71 billion in 
bonds outstanding filed bankruptcy actions 
we expect these trends to continue for at least the next year 
or so he added there will certainly be no shortage of 
bankruptcy securities for turnaround investors to consider 
if the situation creates opportunities it also embodies risks 
and perils that have not yet been fully grasped argues james 
grant whose grants interest rate observer has long warned of 
severe fallout from debt excesses 
if the woes of junk are unique to junk there would be nothing 
to fear in the stock market much less in business activity he 
said 
if however the junk bond markets break is the sign of broad 
distress investors must take appropriate precautions 
in grants view a potentially traumatic move from adventures in 
debt back to traditional financial values is under way 
the thunderheads rolling across the sky are the portents of a 
return to conservative lending he says that is bullish for 
many things in the long pull for the short run however it is not 
bullish for stock prices or for business activity 
</TEXT>
