<TEXT>
long before cable broadcaster ted turner 
began coloring blackandwhite prints margaret spargo was adding a 
blush to the cheeks or a splash of color to the dresses of the 
subjects in her monochrome portraits 
almost daily she sits at a little red table in the window of her 
storefront studio with its old bellows camera in back and its 
shelves piled high with papers photographs and tools of her trade 
carefully coloring photographs by hand 
propped around her are examples of her handiwork a technique 
that is regaining popularity in art schools that makes little 
impression on her 
spargo who wont reveal her age is a woman of few words 
especially describing how she learned her technique nearly 60 years 
ago 
i just did it on my own dont ask me how i learned i just 
did it she says 
working from detailed notes about her subjects she deftly dabs 
nearly transparent oil paint with a piece of cotton onto the faces 
of a mother father and son she had spent several painstaking 
hours working with a colored pencil and brush to match the womans 
blue print dress 
that was a lulu its not quite right but its close she 
said admiring her work and wistfully recalling the days when 
clothes were plainer 
she works quickly with widening circular strokes if she 
strays the paint can be wiped away until it fully dries in about a 
day the artistry comes in blending the colors and highlighting the 
features so the boys blue eyes have a lifelike almost impish 
sparkle 
in spargos typical unconcerned attitude she cant tell you how 
long it takes her to finish a typical photograph 
that sounds silly but ive never timed myself people are 
much too scientific about things she said 
a typical 8 by 10inch tinted portrait of one person costs 50 
but if the customer wants spargo to color with heavier opaque oils 
that must be brushed on it will cost 200 
hand coloring emerged in the 1840s shortly after 
daguerreotypes the first commercially viable photos taken on glass 
plates said david gibney negative archivist of the international 
museum of photography in rochester ny 
at first a little blush was added to the cheeks and a splash of 
color to jewelry fully tinted photos became popular after the turn 
of the century until color photo materials improved and became 
affordable in the 1940s 
i think a lot of sins that the cameras lens brings out can be 
hidden with hand coloring and you can enhance the good things 
gibney said 
it made its resurgence in college fine art programs during the 
past 10 years as an art form said e ken white chairman of fine 
art photography at the rochester institute of technology and 
himself a hand colorer 
workers at john g marshall manufacturing co in chicago the 
major distributor of the special oils only know theyve shipped 
many more paint kits lately 
we get calls every day from practically all over the world 
said margaret heft who helps assemble the kits ive worked for 
the company for nine years and every year its increased 
she estimated the company ships about 50000 tubes of paint and 
kits a year directly to customers compared with about 20000 a 
decade ago and about 10 times that number are shipped through an 
affiliated wholesaler 
even the best color print will begin to age in five years but 
handcolored photos can last 50 years without much deterioration 
white said 
handcolored prints of stilllifes or scenery became a major 
industry around the turn of the century with photographers such as 
wallace natting of boston maintaining stables of retouchers he 
said 
its hard to visit an antiques store in new england and not 
find a wallace natting hanging on the wall somewhere white said 
spargo doesnt recall all the specifics of when she got into the 
business she only remembers that it was sometime in the 1930s and 
she was 19 when she went to work for photographer fred stiles at 
his downtown studio 
she was dissuaded from becoming a nurse by her older sister who 
worked at the local hospital for a summer so she went to stiles 
who had shot her parents wedding photos 
i just thought i wanted to do something that i would learn 
something not just a job she said but after the first day of 
retouching the photo of a boy to remove his freckles she almost 
went looking elsewhere 
stiles told me it looked like a hen scratched it which it 
probably did she said 
but spargo persevered under a succession of owners and four 
years later bought the studio it was at a national photography 
workshop at winona lake ind where she went to learn more about 
commercial photography that she took up hand coloring 
spargo had planned to do color photography but the great 
hurricane of 1938 wiped out much of westerly and made supplies 
hard to get after that other things came up and she just never 
got around to it 
i dont know why she said 
she also does a good business in copying and retouching old 
photographs but discourages people from getting them hand colored 
because they probably dont know what the true colors were 
in her own way she hews to tradition even while adding color 
to black and white and thats why she doesnt like the new trend 
toward colorizing movies 
i like them better in black and white they were made that 
way why change them she said its just a notion i have 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

