<DOCNO> AP900214-0211 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
something strange has been happening lately to 
bluesman bobby radcliff the bikers and flying beer bottles have 
disappeared from his concerts no guns no knives no cops 
suddenly his audiences are no longer confined to drunks aging 
beatniks and hippies yuppies like him jazz collectors too how 
radcliff worries can he keep the blues dirty in front of people so 
wellbehaved 
ive been in these rough and tumble clubs most of my life 
said the 39yearold singerguitarist whose first national release 
is called dresses too short 
just in the last year we played at cbgbs and that went over 
really well and freaked me out a little bit all of a sudden youre 
playing in these big places and its a little unnerving he said 
of the new york club 
we played at the ritz last week youre playing in front of 10 
times an audience ive been in these small clubs where people are 
right in your face you know what theyre thinking what theyre 
feeling and you know how to gauge their response level youll 
play a note and theyll go yeah 
not that radcliff is complaining he has no wish to return to 
the lean times of the mid1970s when a dying blues scene forced 
him to earn a living lifting boxes 
but the blues is a most personal kind of music demanding active 
interchange with an audience radcliff remembered seeing bb king 
in small clubs talking up women while squeezing sounds from his 
beloved guitar lucille 
the intimacy of a small place is pretty cool radcliff said 
thats when you see an audience and a performer come together at 
a nightclub you can start up and mellow out go along and start up 
again youre working in a framework of three or four hours 
in these big rock gigs you got to go right on up and when im 
off i dont feel like im warmed up yet 
radcliff grew up in affluent chevy chase md and by age 12 was 
already checking out live shows around howard university nearby 
washington dc 
our teacher let us out of school early he was one of these 
hip teachers he recalled for 250 youd see three acts 
jimmy reed booker t and the mgs sam and dave across this 
street was this huge record store and wed go buy the records that 
we had heard played 
radcliff loved elvis presley johnny cash and the other early 
rock n roll stars but longed for something more in the early 
1960s he found it the blues first slim harpo then muddy 
waters howlin wolf and dozens of others when he was 16 radcliff 
ran away from home in search of bluesman magic sam who showed his 
young fan around the clubs of chicagos west side 
back home he modeled his singing on elvis and magic sam and 
started playing guitar in local bands giving concerts at churches 
picnics and barbeques by the early 70s he was performing in 
blues clubs notably cousin nicks a tiny bar in northwest 
washington 
sometimes wed go back and hang out in the alley at the rear 
of the club and the bass player almost got his bass stolen from a 
small gang of kids he recalled there were lots of little 
miniholdups and stuff some of our fans would get robbed coming in 
and out of the clubs that was kind of a rough area 
but cousin nicks closed in the mid70s and radcliff bounced 
around california albuquerque nm and washington again before 
settling in new york it was 1977 the discos days the time of 
saturday night fever and donna summer the blues seemed 
outdated and radcliff watched his peers drop out 
they got really depressed wound up drinking themselves under 
the table he said i guess i had some kind of deep belief that 
somehow maybe it would work out even though nothing was there was 
that deep part of me that thought there was some slim chance 
now the blues are back and radcliff has an album on black top 
records major labels were interested but at a price with one 
record company executive even imagining him as a cross between 
elvis and david bowie 
dresses too short is pure radcliff several of the songs 
kool and the gang going home tomorrow hard road to 
travel have been in his live show for years lasting as long as 
the trusty white fender guitar hes owned since the late 60s 
most people will tell me that theres so much garbage on the 
radio radcliff said big companies are not really interested 
in hiring a lot of alternative type bands like blues they want 
bands they can filter through the system 
a lot of the stuff thats out now is not feeling or 
intellectual i like pop myself but i couldnt live on it 
</TEXT>
