<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert incs demise could reach 
far beyond the junkbond sensation it created forcing interest 
rates higher hurting the financing ability of many us companies 
and possibly creating new takeover opportunities for foreign buyers 
investment strategists and business executives said tuesday that 
these were the types of economic consequences to expect from 
drexels decision to seek chapter 11 bankruptcy protection even 
though the investment bank is nowhere near the largest 
when we had the explosion and problems at three mile island 
it impacted the entire utilities industry said paul e berg 
president of berg fiduciary consultants a investment advisory firm 
in port chester ny youve got pretty much the same situation 
here 
the drexel bankruptcy filing could inject more sellers into the 
already depressed junk bond market that the firm dominates 
creating a confidence crisis that might spread into other 
securities some experts said 
such turmoil in turn could have a more profound effect by 
forcing interest rates higher at a time when many economists say 
interest rates must come down if the economy is to avoid a 
recession 
this means that the cost of capital to the united states will 
increase said chriss street a strategist at seidler amdec 
securities inc a los angeles investment firm the cost of 
capital overseas will be relatively lower we should expect a lot 
of acquisitions by foreigners 
to the surprise of some the market for junk bonds survived a 
wave of paranoia tuesday and prices of many issues actually 
stabilized managers of several junkbond mutual funds said they 
didnt receive any flood of calls from investors who wanted to get 
out 
but others said the markets behavior reflected confusion about 
the ultimate impact of drexels problems and they predicted that 
over the next several days at least the demand for junk bonds would 
stall 
its going to be very difficult to find buyers for that 
paper said jack barbanel managing director of first global 
asset management a princeton nj investment concern youll 
find many sellers but not many buyers 
many expressed surprise at the frightening speed with which 
drexel hurtled toward collapse because of the junk bond market it 
largely was responsible for creating in the 1980s 
it took a long time to string together this enterprise and 
not much time at all for it to crack up said james grant author 
of a prominent financial newsletter that frequently has warned 
against the perils of junkbond debt its not unlike the 
collapse of tyson in tokyo 
others likened drexels demise to a disaster that will further 
erode the tarnished credibility of the depressed securities 
industry overall and convince investors to shun investments that 
have no relation to junk bonds 
this could force companies that historically have relied on 
selling stocks and bonds for new capital to curtail spending plans 
lay off workers or even seek bankruptcy protection themselves 
meanwhile banks insurers pension funds mutual funds and 
other investors who bought junk bonds because they promised such 
high rates of interest could wind up owning nearly worthless pieces 
of paper some financial strategists said 
now the reality is beginning to sink in its coming home to 
roost that when people originally called them junk bonds thats 
exactly what they were barbanel said 
others emphasized however that the overall amount of junk 
bonds held by most investors remains only a tiny percentage of 
their portfolios the total value of assets held just by pension 
funds for example is more than 25 trillion while the entire 
junk bond market once amounted to about 200 billion 
if everybody owned a piece of a junk bond it would be pretty 
small said william overgard director of investment consulting 
at buck pension fund services in new york 
drexel vaulted to prominence in the 1980s by aggressively 
peddling highinterest securities with low credit ratings as a way 
to raise money for businesses seeking to expand the securities 
became known as junk bonds because of their relatively higher risk 
of default compared with investmentgrade corporate bonds 
even before drexels latest problems a number of prominent 
deals that depended on junkbond financing had begun unraveling or 
faced serious obstacles drexel played a role in many of them 
on tuesday for example drexel client integrated resources 
inc a diversified financial services company that has been 
struggling for months sought federal bankruptcy protection 
</TEXT>
