<TEXT>
restrictive government policies on both sides 
of the border and antiquated transportation and processing 
facilities threaten the growth in usmexico agricultural trade 
according to a study by congressional investigators 
the general accounting office congress investigative arm said 
trade between the neighboring countries increased from 23 billion 
during the recession year of 1982 to 4 billion in 1988 the 
highest growth rate among major us agricultural trading partners 
while mexico is one of the united states best customers of 
agricultural products gao said several problems continue to impede 
trade including stiff health regulations import licensing 
requirements and tariffs 
mexican growers complain their agricultural exports are subject 
to excessive us plant and animal health regulations and that us 
tariffs on certain crops are too high us sources complain that 
mexicos continued reliance on import licensing requirements is 
inconsistent with international trading laws gao said 
mexicos transportation infrastructure also has been inadequate 
to handle the large increase in trade in recent years and if not 
improved will continue to limit trade volume between the two 
countries said the study requested by us rep kika de la garza 
dtexas 
gao said mexicos rail system is outdated and lacks the capacity 
to carry the increasing cargo from the united states storage 
facilities are also lacking and rail cars are used instead to store 
grain or other goods 
due to delays in returning rail cars to the united states and 
congestion at the border gao said us rail companies refused 
several times last year to accept any mexicanbound shipments 
imposing a de facto embargo 
roads in mexico are in general disrepair making transportation 
of goods by truck a slow process us truckers meanwhile 
complain that they cannot operate in mexico while mexican truckers 
can enter the united states with their cargo 
another problem gao said is that congestion bottlenecks and 
excessive delays characterize conditions at border crossing points 
saul mercado director for latin american affairs at the texas 
department of agriculture said another problem for texas exporters 
is that railroad rates are higher instate than for outofstate 
shippers making it cheaper for someone from kansas to get his 
grain to the border than a texan 
mexican trucks can carry heavier loads than texas law permits 
requiring much costly loading and unloading at the border mercado 
said 
mexico is the no 1 buyer of texas agricultural products 
mercado said 
we export every day livestock and grain and all kinds of 
commodities to mexico mercado said 
the state which has a positive balance of trade with mexico 
lists its top exports as cattle for breeding sheep goats and hogs 
for slaughter and a few dairy cows and some horses the state also 
ships corn sorghum rice and some wheat 
mexico provides the united states with tropical products and 
specialty crops such as coffee and tomatoes 
mexicos outstanding external debt which totaled more than 100 
billion in 1988 is also a major constraint to trade gao said 
despite those problems mexico bought more agricultural products 
from the united states than all but three other countries in 1988 
japan south korea and the soviet union with a total value of 
223 billion 
mexico in turn ranked third among all agricultural suppliers 
to the united states after canada and brazil providing the us 
with 182 billion in foodstuffs two years ago 
the united states had a positive agricultural trade balance in 
1988 with mexico of about 414 million 
