<TEXT>
maryland tobacco growers may soon end a centuries old tradition 
of handtying hands of tobacco leaves opting instead for 
70pound bales that could cut labor costs by as much as 30 percent 
its the first major change in the form of marketing tobacco 
in more than 350 years said claude mckee director of the 
university of marylands experimental tobacco farm near upper 
marlboro 
the state department of agriculture has announced that at least 
two major buyers have agreed to purchase maryland tobacco that is 
baled and a third has given informal approval 
mckee said he approached tobacco companies with the proposal and 
has received written agreements from phillip morris cos inc and 
universal leaf tobacco co 
traditionally workers have spent the fall and winter months 
preparing for the spring auction by tying bundles of 25 to 30 
leaves of similar quality into a fanshaped hand using the stem of 
one leaf 
bales of tobacco measure three feet by two feet by one foot and 
weigh about 70 pounds mckee said buyers have expressed a desire to 
have uniform bales throughout the industry 
it would be a change from an antiquated way and it could put 
more money in the farmers pocket said maryland agriculture 
secretary wayne cawley 
whether the change occurs however depends on if buyers will 
pay as much for baled tobacco as they do for handtied tobacco 
cawley said 
cawley said an effort to change to bales three years ago failed 
because buyers at auctions declined to pay as much for baled 
tobacco 
baling was first used in the burley tobacco region kentucky 
tennessee west virginia north carolina and missouri about 10 
years ago and almost all burley tobacco is now baled 
my feeling is that the ground has been broken mckee said 
one or two will lead the way and the rest will follow it could 
be a big breakthrough a real laborsaver 
