<DOCNO> AP900214-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
toshiba corp has developed a prototype of a 
4megabit static random access memory chip company officials said 
wednesday 
toshiba said the new 4megabit sram is the first to use 
thinfilm transistors as memory cells a technology that reduces 
power consumption 
sram chips are more complex than the more common dynamic random 
access memory chips which are already available in 4megabit 
capacity sram chips generally use less power than drams and do not 
need special refresh circuits to retain their information 
making them wellsuited to batterypowered equipment like laptop 
computers 
however the larger number of transistors used by srams make 
them harder to design and manufacture than drams with the same 
memory capacity 
toshiba said the new chip has the same circuit density as 
16megabit drams which are expected to be the next generation of 
memory chips 
on tuesday ibm said it has begun producing 16megabit drams on 
a trial basis but said commercial production could be at least 18 
months away 
a toshiba official said his company does not know when the 
4megabit sram will go into commercial production currently the 
largest commercially available sram is 1 megabit 
a 4megabit memory chip can store about 4 million binary units 
of information or the equivalent of about 16 newspaper pages 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

