<DOCNO> AP900214-0236 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the amazing thing about almost all financial 
debacles is that those involved know better but allow their 
negative feelings to be overcome by the lure of big profits 
it happens regularly 
when bankers clamped down on home mortgage loans in the 1970s 
because they said such loans could be risky they lent hundreds 
of millions of dollars to less developed nations in order to obtain 
premium interest rates from then 
it was well known at the time that the loans were hazardous and 
might not be repaid banker magazines warned of the practice and 
even the general media carried interviews with analysts who 
accurately forecast what would happen 
still the chairman of one of the nations largest banks 
repeatedly scorned the warnings suggesting the writers were 
uninformed these loans he said are backed by the full faith and 
credit of governments theyre secure he said 
it happened in texas real estate and later in new england 
everybody in the building and real estate knows from experience 
that their occupation is cyclical everyone in banking should know 
that the economy as a whole is cyclical that it expands and 
contracts repeatedly 
it didnt stop them builders built and lenders lent and each 
one thought they would be the exception as if the gods were 
watching over them they gambled that they would close their deals 
before the downturn began 
the serious problem with that thinking is that the line is never 
drawn and each lender and builder tries just one more time 
they might be forgiven for not anticipating a sudden disaster 
such as a collapse of oil prices but they certainly had to know 
that in the natural cycle of events building booms come to an end 
often abruptly 
moreover a boom exaggerated by excessive lending is almost 
guaranteed to blow up nothing new in that theyve all seen it 
before 
it happened with the savings and loan associations 
while managers of some sampls seemed not to know what they were 
doing since deregulation of financial institutions had opened up 
brand new lending investing opportunities for them seasoned 
managers understood very well 
they understood risk and they understood high investment 
returns knowing that their practices couldnt continue forever 
they nevertheless felt they could cash in on a good thing just one 
more time soon they couldnt get out 
among the many problems that worsens greed is secrecy no lender 
wanted another to know that they were going to take just one more 
risk finance just one more building and then get out so they 
all took one more risk 
as a result the nation suddenly had more office space more 
industrial space more housing than it needed and all those 
beautiful projections that looked so good on paper were seen for 
what they were unsubstantiated hopes 
now we have junk bonds or highyield credit instruments 
designed to finance the very riskiest of enterprises such as 
takeovers 
those who developed the idea knew the risks were great but what 
is risk they asked but the other side of the coin doesnt 
everyone know that reward is in direct ratio to the risk assumed 
junk bonds were bought by the most highly educated and 
supposedly savvy portfolio managers those who guided the affairs 
of foundations mutual and pension funds university endowments and 
the like the lure overcame them 
in none of these instances was the collapse general although it 
was total in specific individual instances some investors have 
indeed benefited the reward for assuming high risk and in the 
future others will 
while the lure of big money is likely to produce future 
financial devices of the same sort others probably will learn a 
lesson 
many banks for example are reexamining standards on home 
equity loans known less euphemistically as second mortgages those 
loans have proliferated in recent years an economic decline could 
put some of them in foreclosure 
one tipoff is that some bank customers are working two jobs just 
to pay the interest a warning sign 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

