<DOCNO> AP900214-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
world trade negotiators agreed on a plan of action 
wednesday to liberalize trade in the 100 billion tropical products 
market ending months of stalemate 
the agreement clears the way for a new accord to reduce import 
barriers and duties on products such as nuts coffee and spices to 
be signed when the current round of general agreement on tariff and 
trade talks ends in december 
under the plan each gatt member has to submit proposals for the 
elimination or reduction of its respective tariffs and nontariff 
measures to the genevabased secretariat by march 15 
negotiators will then meet in april to discuss whether the 
various proposals go far enough to meet the gattsponsored uruguay 
rounds objectives on the fullest liberalization of trade in 
tropical products 
when the fouryear round was launched in punte del este in 1986 
governments agreed to pay due regard to eliminating duties on 
unprocessed tropical products to abolishing or cutting duties on 
semiprocessed and processed products and eliminating or cutting 
nontariff measures such as quotas 
as a first step toward these goals ministers meeting in 
montreal in december 1988 agreed on a package of trading 
concessions to developing countries worth some 20 billion dollars 
however negotiations were subsequently held up by the impasse 
over an internationallyagreed approach to cutting overall tariffs 
a compromise formula was agreed last month freeing the way for 
progress in talks on tropical products 
trade officials were also expected to reach agreement wednesday 
on a schedule for proposals aimed at cutting nontariff measures in 
a wide range of products 
a new accord to free trade in tropical products is regarded as 
vital by third world countries many of whom are dependent on 
export earnings from these commodities 
although tariffs on tropical products are generally low they 
are also selective according to a gatt official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
the official cited the example of colombia which faces tariffs 
of about 20 percent on sales of cut flowers one of its most 
important exports to the european community flowers from israel 
entering the ec by contrast are not subject to duties he said 
gatt is the main international forum for sponsoring trade 
negotiations its 96 members account for about fourfifths of world 
trade 
</TEXT>
