<TEXT>
the financial services industry which reshaped 
corporate america in the 1980s with highrisk junk bond financing 
is undergoing a restructuring that will lead to more conservative 
lending policies experts said at a conference board gathering 
wednesday 
separately economists participating in the groups twoday 
conference on the financial outlook for 1990 generally predicted 
the us economy would avoid a recession this year although 
inflation would rise 
the financial difficulties of drexel burnham lambert inc whose 
parent filed for bankruptcy court protection on tuesday 
illustrated the problems facing the entire industry 
drexel pioneered the use of highrisk highinterest junk bonds 
for a range of corporate financing spurring the wave of mergers 
and buyouts that reshaped corporate american in the 1980s but the 
firm ran into financial trouble when that market stumbled 
senior conference board economist vincent g massaro said that 
in 1981 roughly 7 percent of total corporate debt was rated 
speculative by moodys investors service inc the rating 
agency last month the figure was 20 percent he said 
the percentage of companies sales that goes toward debt 
payments has risen to the point where it has eroded competition 
within some sectors of corporate america said moodys president 
john a bohn jr 
he predicted the issuance of speculativegrade bonds 
otherwise known as junk bonds would plunge by at least 50 percent 
this year and that attitudes would shift toward financial 
conservatism 
leveraged buyout and takeover activity as a driving force 
will fade bohn said 
in another area experts agreed the united states would escape a 
recession this year but said challenges on both domestic and 
international fronts will test the economys ability to sustain its 
recordsetting expansion 
thhe united states will face challenges from several directions 
according to bohn usjapan relations will be put to the test in 
the coming years and banks will be pressed to resume lending to 
less developed countries to get their economies going and in 
eastern europe the stage is set for a new range of eastwest 
trade and financial incentives he noted 
how the united states will fare with these longterm challenges 
is unclear economic growth will continue at roughly a 25 percent 
pace this year massaro said but inflation will rise to between 5 
percent and 6 percent 
i see the us economy in a late phase of the cycle a time 
when prudent decisionmakers will guard their flanks massaro 
said 
the conference board is a nonprofit network of companies trade 
and professional organizations government agencies and labor 
unions 
