<DOCNO> AP900214-0259 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the collapse of drexel burnham lambert maybe 
another blow to an already teetering market for junk bond financed 
takeovers but dealmakers are showing they still have plenty of 
ways to do business 
georgiapacific corp is undertaking a 38 billion hostile bid 
for rival paper manufacturer great northern nekoosa inc and the 
management of chryslers gulfstream aerospace subsidiary is buying 
the division for 825 million 
the bidders for those companies have gone back to some older 
more conservative financing methods as other corporate borrowers 
that once relied on the junk market may now be forced to do 
the takeover business slowed to a crawl when junk bond money 
dried up last fall after serious problems emerged at a number of 
companies heavily financed with the highinterest debt 
the bankruptcy court filing late tuesday by the parent of drexel 
whose fortunes rose and fell with the market for the highyield 
debt securities that it pioneered was another devastating blow to 
junk bond financing once the premier route for backing a buyout 
georgiapacific has lined up financing from a syndicate of banks 
at an interest rate of 1 percent above the prime rate which 
currently stands at 10 percent that compares with the 16 percent 
levels commonly attached to junk bonds 
being able to do the deal without junk bonds was one of its 
selling points said ad pete correll georgiapacifics 
executive vice president in charge of pulp and paper 
gulfstream meanwhile is being bought with bank financing and a 
combination of equity and debt financing provided by the divisions 
chairman alan paulson and the investment firm forstmann little amp 
co 
paulson said he never considered using junk bonds 
junk bonds began falling seriously out of favor in september 
when campeau corps 67 billion purchase of federated department 
stores inc which depended heavily on the risky securities 
began to unravel a number of new junk bond financings were put on 
hold 
the junk bond market has taken a series of hits since then and 
drexel whose biggest business was selling the securities suffered 
heavy losses that contributed to the firms chapter 11 filing 
already dim prospects for takeover entrepreneurs to raise 
large amounts of money using highyield bonds is further dimmed 
this is another significant negative said gregg a jarrell a 
finance professor at the university of rochesters william e simon 
school of business 
morris mendelson a professor of finance at the university of 
pennsylvanias wharton school of business said drexels downfall 
wont kill the junk bond market but i suspect that some firms 
that might have been able to raise money in the junk bond market 
while drexel was alive wont be able to now 
bernard black a columbia university school of law professor 
said the junk bond market would shrink drexels problems mean a 
possible source of liquidity is no longer there he said 
theres no market maker for recently issued debt 
junk bonds are best known for backing big takeovers but they 
also have been used extensively by smaller companies some of these 
firms resorted to highyield debt because they could not obtain 
other financing and may face trouble if they need loans in the 
future 
they may be slower in their growth said allen michel a 
professor at the boston university school of management they 
will not be able to expand at the same rate theyll have to pull 
in their horns 
mendelson painted a darker picture you may have more firms 
going bellyup that wouldnt have had to go bellyup before 
investors pursuing buyouts are finding that the failure of junk 
bonds has created problems besides forcing them to look for other 
means of financing trying to get bank financing means meeting a 
newly toughened set of qualifications 
in junk bond financing hundreds of individual investors might 
be putting up 1 million for many of them a relatively small 
amount but a bank syndicate has a smaller number of participants 
who have much more at stake and therefore more stringent standards 
said jerome e hass a professor of managerial economics and 
finance at cornell universitys johnson graduate school of 
management 
what they want is a business that has a cash flow capacity to 
service the debt hass said of lenders 
georgiapacific said it expects to have a debt load of 75 
billion if it succeeds in its bid for great northern securities 
analysts who track the company say that the suitor and its target 
have strong cash flows and say georgiapacific will be able to pay 
down its debt 
lawrence ross an analyst with painewebber inc said banks also 
were willing to back georgiapacific because it is tremendously 
strong financially and operationally 
furthermore were not talking here about someone from outside 
the industry taking over a company somebody who doesnt know 
anything about the industry ross said 
</TEXT>
