<DOCNO> AP900214-0265 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a brief explanation of junk bonds and 
their role in the nations financial markets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
corporate bonds rated below investment grade by either standard 
amp poors corp or moodys investors service are considered 
junk that means a companys ability to pay interest and repay 
principal is considered speculative meaning there is a higher risk 
of default to compensate the bonds carry higher yields 
currently an average of 1535 percent compared with 962 percent 
for investmentgrade corporate bonds and 832 percent for 10year 
us government bonds according to moodys 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
moodys estimates there are more than 200 billion in junk bonds 
outstanding representing about 25 percent of all corporate bond 
issues the market mushroomed in the 1980s growing almost nine 
times in size 
in contrast all debt issued by the nations nonfinancial 
concerns which includes government borrowings totals about 96 
trillion the nations equity market or stocks is worth about 
32 trillion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert inc propelled the markets growth and 
was by far the biggest underwriter and trader of junk bonds the 
firm promoted the use of junk bonds to raise money for small or 
young companies unable to issue investmentgrade bonds and to 
finance corporate takeovers drexel says 59 percent of the money 
raised by junk issues from 1980 to 1988 went to finance companies 
internal growth while the remaining 41 percent was used to finance 
takeovers 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
they range from young fastgrowing companies such as mci 
communications corp and mccaw cellular communications inc to 
acquired corporations such as federated department stores inc and 
rjr nabisco federated and rjr issued billions of dollars worth of 
bonds to finance their takeovers by campeau corp and buyout 
specialist kohlberg kravis roberts amp co respectively 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the biggest owners of junk bonds are mutual funds and insurance 
companies each of which holds about 30 percent of the bonds 
outstanding moodys estimates pension funds hold about 15 percent 
of the market foreign investors about 9 percent and savings and 
loan associations about 7 percent the sampl bailout bill passed late 
last year by congress requires thrifts to sell their junk holdings 
by 1994 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900214-0266 </DOCNO>
