<TEXT>
atampt reported a slight increase in 
long distance telephone calls wednesday as the company offered 
valentines day discounts to make up for a ninehour service 
disruption last month 
call volume was up about 1 percent from 8 am to 5 pm the 
hours of the special atampt spokesman mike keady said there were 
about 786 million calls attempted during those hours up from 777 
million the previous wednesday he said 
the long distance network handles about 110 million calls on a 
normal business day 
the discount applied to residential and most business customers 
including credit card and tollfree 800 calls 
a programming error in atampts call switching network partially 
knocked out longdistance service nationwide for about nine hours 
jan 15 keeping millions of calls from being completed 
lynn newman another spokesperson at atampts operations 
headquarters in basking ridge said the discount was the only 
measure planned by atampt to compensate customers 
this is our way of saying youre a valuable customer ms 
newman said 
the phone giant offered longdistance customers an average 33 
percent discount off regular daytime rates for calls within the 
united states between 8 am and 5 pm discounts averaged about 37 
percent off calls to 158 countries worldwide 
in some states where local utility regulators gave the company 
permission discounts also applied to intrastate calls handled by 
atampt she said 
i think its a very generous way for them to atone for any 
damages done said jim furlong spokesman for computer sciences 
corp of los angeles a computer services company that relies 
heavily on long distance calling 
furlong said the company did not attempt to determine how much 
money if any it lost during the ninehour outage 
were not the least bothered or concerned by that oneday 
problem he said 
its a very nice gesture said roger connor a spokesman for 
marriott corp which relies on longdistance telephone calls for 
reservations for its 530 hotels worldwide i think its more than 
adequate 
connor said the company did not believe it lost money because of 
the outage 
mary oneill a spokeswoman for american airlines said her 
company was trying to work out compensation for the outage that 
affected reservation lines last month 
because we had a special corporate contract we were not 
eligible for that discount said ms oneill she said the 
airlines is negotiating with atampt to find an acceptable 
settlement 
she said americans volume of calls was reduced by about 
twothirds on the day of the outage 
