<TEXT>
unsecured creditors of eastern airlines said 
tuesday they would work with the carrier to reach agreement on a 
bankruptcy reorganization plan rather than push for easterns 
liquidation 
the committee representing unsecured creditors a group composed 
mainly of trade suppliers such as aircraft manufacturers who are 
owed about 11 billion by eastern made the announcement after 
meeting in new york 
in a statement the committee said it was briefed by its 
financial advisers about easterns proposed reorganization plan 
other reorganization alternatives and the potential recovery to 
be achieved in a liquidation 
eastern proposed only partial repayment of its debts in its 
latest reorganization proposal filed with the federal bankruptcy 
court in new york in late january previously the carrier had 
promised to repay its debts in full 
the creditors committee has made no determination to pursue a 
liquidation in this case the unsecured creditors statement said 
the creditors committee intends to proceed with immediate 
negotiations with eastern texas air and the examiner with a view 
toward achieving a consensual plan of reorganization that is in the 
best interests of creditors and which provides for a viable eastern 
airlines going forward 
eastern spokesman robin matell welcomed the creditors committee 
statement 
we look forward to continuing negotiations with the committee 
in hopes of reaching a consensual agreement he said late tuesday 
easterns reorganization plan calls for paying unsecured 
creditors only 10 percent of their debts in cash when the airline 
emerges from bankruptcy protection and another 70 percent over the 
following 10 years without interest 
in return for accepting partial repayment texas air would give 
the unsecured creditors a 40 percent equity stake in eastern 
the plan also calls for paying preferred stockholders no more 
than 10 cents on the dollar in the form of new securities the 
preferred holders who are owed 1175 billion criticized 
easterns reorganization plans and advocated the liquidation or 
outright sale of the airline two weeks 
the machinists union has been on strike against eastern since 
last march 4 it was joined in sympathy walkouts by pilots and 
flight attendants forcing the airline into bankruptcy court 
protection on march 9 the pilots and flight attendants abandoned 
their strikes just before thanksgiving but eastern has rebuilt as 
a smaller carrier and hired mostly nonunion workers to replace the 
strikers 
</TEXT>
